 "_creativity_chain_quotes": [
  "A feedback controller needs two things to hold a state: a set-point (the target) and an error signal (distance from target). Development supplies a moving reference -- the growth trajectory from zygote to adult -- and the insulin/IGF-1 -> AKT -> mTORC1 network executes it... At maturity the trajectory ends, but nothing defines 'the adult state to be maintained indefinitely,' because the force of natural selection falls after reproduction... The result is a controller with a reference but no terminal hold-state. [Commission] Growth-type signalling continues into adulthood... [Omission] The high-mTORC1 state suppresses autophagy and repair... Hyperfunction predicts aging rate proportional to absolute mTOR activity. The set-point principle predicts rate proportional to reference error... hold absolute mTOR fixed and supply a competing stationary reference / error-correction while holding damage load fixed. Hyperfunction predicts no change; the set-point principle predicts the aging rate slows.",
